Cabrillo National Monument is located on Point Loma, a high bluff at the entrance to San Diego harbor in California. Named after Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo, who, in 1542, was the first European to explore the west coast of the United States. Highlights of the park are Old Point Loma Lighthouse, the rugged shoreline, and the sweeping views across San Diego harbor.

This was take at Cabrillo National Monument on Point Loma in San Diego, California. This time of year the fog is very prevalent along our coast and even has a name...."June Gloom". The air temperature when I took this was probably 65 - 70 degrees F. The water temperature is about 63 degrees, but fifty miles east of here, in our deserts, the air temperature is over 100 degrees. This differential causes winds from the ocean and cool temperatures along the coast. The result is that it's wonderful to live close to the coast in the summer, if you like cooler weather. My daughter spent one summer living in Carlsbad, and said she never saw the sun. <a href"http:bighugelabs.comonblack.php?id4702099004&sizelarge" rel"nofollow">View Large On Black<a>

This nudibranch feeds on a species of hydroid (Eudendrium ramosum), which possesses a pigment called astaxanthin. This pigment gives the Spanish shawl nudibranch its brilliant color. In the Spanish shawl nudibranch, the astaxanthin shows up in 3 different states, creating the purple, orange and red colors found on this species. Astaxanthin is also found in other marine creatures, including lobsters (which contributes to the lobster's red appearance when cooked), krill, and salmon. <a href"http:marinelife.about.comodinvertebratespSpanish-Shawl-Nudibranch-Flabellina-iodinea.htm" rel"nofollow">marinelife.about.comodinvertebratespSpanish-Shawl-Nud...<a>

The Spanish shawl nudibranch (Flabellina iodinea), also known as the purple aeolis, is a striking nudibranch, with a purple or bluish body, red rhinophores and orange cerata. Spanish shawl nudibranchs can grow to about 2.75 inches in length. <a href"http:marinelife.about.comodinvertebratespSpanish-Shawl-Nudibranch-Flabellina-iodinea.htm" rel"nofollow">marinelife.about.comodinvertebratespSpanish-Shawl-Nud...<a>

This nudibranch displays a stunning set of colors: the body is purple, the cerata are orange and the rhinophores are scarlet. The neon orange appendages on the back of Flabellina iodinea are the cerata which extract oxygen from the sea water they live in. The cerata are also extensions of the digestive system, and are used to store the stinging cells of the anemones and fan-like hydroids they eat. The red rhinophores are sensory structures used for detecting the presence of possible mates and prey. The purple, red, and orange colors are derived from a single carotenoid pigment, astaxanthin. The pigment appears in three modified states, leading to the three distinct colors.[2] <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiSpanish_shawl" rel"nofollow">en.wikipedia.orgwikiSpanish_shawl<a>
